## Responsibilities
- Implement the assigned backend feature, API, or business logic according to task artifacts
- Write tests for all new code before considering the task complete
- Commit progress regularly and signal task.completed or handoff.prepared when done

## Work Standards
- Write tests alongside implementation — do not defer testing to the end
- Validate inputs at system boundaries; trust internal interfaces
- Keep functions focused and files under ~300 lines — split when they grow
- Use clear, intention-revealing names; avoid abbreviations
- Never commit secrets, credentials, or environment config — use environment variables
- Never commit `.aom/` directory files — `git add -A` will include `.aom/sessions.db`
  (a binary SQLite file) if it is tracked; this makes git slow and causes background
  terminal accumulation. `.aom/` must be in `.gitignore` before the first commit.
- **Workspace agents (codex)**: your workspace is shown in .agent/task.md under "Artifact Root".
  Verify with `pwd` before creating files. Do NOT write files to parent directories or the
  git repo root — all output must stay inside your workspace directory.
- Prefer explicit error handling; no silent failures or broad catch-all blocks
- Remove dead code and unused imports before each commit

## Sandbox Constraints
- Outbound network access is enabled — npm install / pip install / go get should work normally
- The sandbox sets `npm_config_cache=/tmp/aom-npm-cache-<uid>` automatically to prevent
  EPERM errors from the default ~/.npm cache path; do NOT override this variable
- If a package install fails: do NOT retry in a loop — write stub/placeholder code,
  note "requires: npm install post-merge" in .agent/state.md, and continue
- If git commit fails or hangs:
  use `aom worktree commit --local -m "<message>"` as the fallback
- If a command hangs: press Ctrl+C once, then report via `aom message send`
- Always cd into the correct subdirectory before running npm/pip/go commands

## Workspace Agent Commit Convention

If your workspace is a permanent per-agent worktree (you never cd to a per-task worktree),
your branch is shared across tasks. **Prefix every commit with `[TASK-xxx]`** where xxx
matches the current task ID (shown in `.agent/task.md` under "Task ID").

Example:
  git add -A && git commit -m "[TASK-abc-1] add POST /users endpoint with tests"

AOM reads this tag at merge time (`aom merge commit`) to identify which commits belong
to which task. A commit without the prefix will be excluded from the task's merge set.

## Completion Signal

After committing, always signal completion with:
  aom task signal task.completed --task <task-id> --summary "<what was delivered>"

**Do NOT use `aom task close`** — that is an operator command and will not write the
completion event that `aom task verify` looks for. Only `aom task signal task.completed`
passes the verify gate.
